WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:05.960 --> 00:00:11.320
Good day. I'm Norman Wildberger. Today we're&nbsp;
going to introduce a new type of mathematical&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:11.320 --> 00:00:18.440
object called a fraction, and defining a fraction&nbsp;
precisely is a significant challenge. There are&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:18.440 --> 00:00:22.920
many different points of view that one could&nbsp;
possibly take. We're going to approach things&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:22.920 --> 00:00:29.200
from a foundational point of view, meaning&nbsp;
we're interested in something which has very&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:29.200 --> 00:00:36.560
few prerequisites and is just based on what we've&nbsp;
done so far, starting from natural numbers. Let's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:36.560 --> 00:00:42.480
introduce the idea that a mathematical object&nbsp;
has a certain type. So far, we only have natural&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:42.480 --> 00:00:50.760
numbers, and they are of type N, standing for&nbsp;
natural number. Here's a summary of the operations&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:50.760 --> 00:01:00.000
that we have so far that are inputting numbers&nbsp;
or pairs of numbers and outputting numbers.

00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:07.480
We want to introduce new objects called fractions,&nbsp;
like 2/3 or this one here, and we want to do this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:07.480 --> 00:01:14.680
for a number of reasons. First of all, we&nbsp;
want to be able to do arithmetic smoothly,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:14.680 --> 00:01:25.440
so when we have 24/6 * 15/5, we know we can&nbsp;
rewrite that as 24 * 15 / 6 * 5. The way we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:25.440 --> 00:01:30.680
are doing arithmetic suggests that we should be&nbsp;
able to swap these around, replace it with 5 * 6,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:30.680 --> 00:01:41.440
and then rewrite this as 24 / 5 * 15 / 6. However,&nbsp;
currently, these are not well-defined operations.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:41.440 --> 00:01:51.520
We cannot currently divide 24 by 5 nor 15 by 6, so&nbsp;
currently, this kind of operation is not defined.

00:01:51.520 --> 00:01:57.600
There are various approaches to fractions. One&nbsp;
of them is to think of a fraction as a part of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:57.600 --> 00:02:04.560
a whole. So if we represent one not just with a&nbsp;
little stick but let's say a square or possibly&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:04.560 --> 00:02:11.400
a circle, then we would represent two as a pair&nbsp;
of squares or a pair of circles, and then it's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:11.400 --> 00:02:21.440
natural to think of 2/3 as representing a part&nbsp;
of one, in this case, the red part. That's one&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:21.440 --> 00:02:27.240
way of thinking about what a fraction like 2/3&nbsp;
means. Another way of thinking about it is in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:27.240 --> 00:02:32.240
terms of the measure of a segment. If we think&nbsp;
of one as representing a segment like this,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:32.240 --> 00:02:36.760
then something like three will be represented&nbsp;
by a longer segment like that, and then it's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:36.760 --> 00:02:42.120
natural to think about a shorter segment, perhaps&nbsp;
like that one, as being a representation of what&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:42.120 --> 00:02:48.680
2/3 means. Similarly, if we look at this longer&nbsp;
segment and divide it by two, then we get the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:48.680 --> 00:02:57.520
fraction 3/2. So that's a derivation of what&nbsp;
fractions are, connecting it with geometry.

00:02:57.520 --> 00:03:02.200
Another way of thinking about fractions is&nbsp;
as an operation. So we think of 2/3 as being&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:02.200 --> 00:03:07.800
an operation that allows us to take 2/3 of&nbsp;
something. Here's a collection of things;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:07.800 --> 00:03:14.400
2/3 of this collection is this collection. So&nbsp;
it's an operator that acts on something to give&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:14.400 --> 00:03:21.520
you something else. Another way of thinking about&nbsp;
it is as a ratio or a proportion. For example,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:21.520 --> 00:03:28.040
2/3 can be thought of as the ratio or&nbsp;
proportion 2 to 3, and we can imagine&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:28.040 --> 00:03:36.960
that by comparing two objects, the relative&nbsp;
sizes of those two objects might be 2 to 3.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:36.960 --> 00:03:41.480
There are various possible ways of thinking&nbsp;
about fractions, and each one of them has&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:41.480 --> 00:03:48.880
some usefulness and validity and can be used&nbsp;
as a basis for teaching young people. However,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:48.880 --> 00:03:54.760
when we do mathematics, we want to set things&nbsp;
up in such a way as not to require a prior&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:54.760 --> 00:04:01.720
understanding of geometry. We want something that&nbsp;
only depends on what we've already done before,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:01.720 --> 00:04:06.280
and so we're going to use a slightly different&nbsp;
way of thinking about what a fraction is.

00:04:06.280 --> 00:04:16.160
Here is our main definition: a fraction is&nbsp;
an ordered pair (M, N) of natural numbers.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:16.160 --> 00:04:22.480
So it's just two natural numbers, one followed&nbsp;
by the other, an ordered pair, and we also write&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:22.480 --> 00:04:33.280
this ordered pair in the form m/n. That's what a&nbsp;
fraction is—a mathematical definition. And there's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:33.280 --> 00:04:43.680
an important notion of equality that occurs with&nbsp;
fractions. If we have two fractions, m/n and k/l,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:45.040 --> 00:04:56.040
then these two fractions are declared to&nbsp;
be equal precisely when m * l = n * k. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:56.040 --> 00:05:09.280
for example, 2/3 = 6/9 because 2 * 9 is equal to&nbsp;
3 * 6, and both of those are equal to 4/6 and to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:09.280 --> 00:05:16.840
many other ones. That's a definition of fraction&nbsp;
that only depends on our prior understanding of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:16.840 --> 00:05:25.960
what a natural number is—a fraction is just a&nbsp;
pair of natural numbers which we write as m/n.

00:05:25.960 --> 00:05:30.480
Now there's a possible confusion here with our&nbsp;
earlier notation, and let's make sure we get&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:30.480 --> 00:05:38.320
this straight. Right now, let's say we have 15/5&nbsp;
with this slanted line. That represents for us a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:38.320 --> 00:05:45.880
fraction, and it's a new type of mathematical&nbsp;
object which we'll call F, short for fraction.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:45.880 --> 00:05:58.000
15/5 with a horizontal line like that represents a&nbsp;
division; that is a number still in the type num.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:58.000 --> 00:06:05.080
So from now on, we're going to distinguish between&nbsp;
a horizontal line, which means division of one&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:05.080 --> 00:06:10.960
natural number by another, and the slanted&nbsp;
line, which represents a fraction for us.

00:06:10.960 --> 00:06:13.920
Well, now that we have fractions, we&nbsp;
can naturally ask how we are going to do&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:13.920 --> 00:06:18.000
arithmetic with them. That's what we're&nbsp;
going to talk about in the next video.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:18.000 --> 00:06:28.360
I hope you'll join me. I'm Norman&nbsp;
Wildberger. Thanks for listening.

